{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628734"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17234"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17234"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69500"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9924"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17234"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54952"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7616"},{"type":"tags","id":"10700"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23275"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69500"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGene expression is regulated by various DNA sequence elements that interact with transcription factors. Some of these elements act to decrease or prevent gene transcription.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristics of silencer elements in gene regulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Only function when located upstream of the promoter","Only work in combination with enhancer elements","Must be located within 100 base pairs of the gene","Require direct contact with RNA polymerase","Function independently of distance and orientation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilencer elements function independently of distance and orientation\u003C/strong\u003E relative to their target genes. They can be located upstream, downstream, or within genes, and can act over long distances through DNA looping when bound by transcription factors.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly function when located upstream of the promoter\u003C/strong\u003E - Silencers can function from various positions relative to the gene\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequire direct contact with RNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E - Silencers typically work through transcription factors and co-repressors rather than direct polymerase contact\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly work in combination with enhancer elements\u003C/strong\u003E - Silencers can function independently of enhancers\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMust be located within 100 base pairs of the gene\u003C/strong\u003E - Silencers can function over much greater distances through DNA looping\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003ESilencers play crucial roles in gene regulation by recruiting transcriptional repressors and modifying chromatin structure to reduce gene expression in a controlled manner.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Silencers are DNA regulatory sequences that reduce gene transcription when bound by transcription factors.","Silencers can function at variable distances and orientations from the gene they regulate.","Multiple silencer elements can work together to achieve precise control of gene expression."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54952"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17234"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54952"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T10:10:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T10:13:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9924"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69500"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udee7","name":"Cell Biology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"gr